'''PS ''Slieve Bearnagh''''' was a United Kingdom passenger [[paddle steamer]] that in later years was called '''''HC5'''''. [[John Brown & Company#J&G Thomson|J&G Thomson]] launched her in 1893<ref name=Clyde/> or 1894{{sfn|McCutcheon|1980|p=149}} for the [[Belfast and County Down Railway]] (B&CDR). In 1912 she was sold to D&J Nicol of Dundee.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}} Around the end of the First World War she served with the [[Royal Navy]] as hospital carrier ship ''HC5''.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|pp=13–14}} She was scrapped in 1923.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}}

==With the B&CDR==
[[John Brown & Company#J&G Thomson|J&G Thomson]] of [[Clydebank]] built the ship for the B&CDR,{{sfn|McCutcheon|1980|p=149}} who named her ''[[Slieve Bearnagh]]'' after the second highest peak in the [[Mourne Mountains]] in [[County Down]].{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=13}} Sources disagree as to whether she was launched on 21 November 1893<ref name=Clyde/> or 21 March 1894.{{sfn|McCutcheon|1980|p=149}} She made her trial run on [[Belfast Lough]] on 1 May 1894{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}}

In the spring of 1893 Thomson had built the slightly smaller steamer {{PS|Slieve Donard}} for the B&CDR.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=13}} In May 1894 ''Slieve Bearnagh'' joined ''Slieve Donard'' on the company's regular steamship route between [[Belfast]] and [[Bangor, County Down|Bangor]],{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=13}}{{sfn|McCutcheon|1980|p=149}} for which the scheduled journey time was 55 minutes.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}}

Between them the two ships made six sailings per day from Belfast to Bangor from Mondays to Saturdays and a similar number back to Belfast.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}} There were five sailings on Sundays, and from Mondays to Saturdays one sailing per day extended beyond Bangor to [[Donaghadee]].{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}} On Saturday afternoons other sailings continued from Bangor across Belfast Lough to [[Larne]].{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}}

The railway sold ''Donard'' in 1899 but kept ''Bearnagh'' until 1912.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=13}} She occasionally made excursions to [[Portaferry]] on the [[Ards Peninsula]], [[Ardglass]] in south Down, and [[Larne]] and [[Portrush]] on the coast of [[County Antrim]] in addition to her regular scheduled route on Belfast Lough.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=13}}

The [[Board of Trade]] certificated ''Slieve Bearnagh'' to carry 958 passengers along the coast between Belfast and Bangor or 871 passengers on the more open sea voyage between Belfast and Larne.{{sfn|McCutcheon|1980|p=149}} A report by the B&CDR's General Manager records that in November 1904 her [[Master mariner|Master]], Captain McCorquodale, was [[summons]]ed for overloading the ship.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.countydownrailwaymuseum.org.uk/BCDR%20Staff%20Alphabetical.xls |title=1845 – 1948 Belfast and County Down Railway Staff Register |publisher=Belfast and County Down Railway Museum Trust |date= |accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref>

At the end of the 1911 summer season the B&CDR ordered a replacement ship for £24,000{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}} and put ''Slieve Bearnagh'' up for sale for £12,000.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=13}} No-one offered to buy at that price so the railway reduced it to £10,000 by the end of 1911 and later to £7,000.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=13}} The replacement ship, the slightly larger [[HMS Erin's Isle|PS ''Erin's Isle'']], was launched on 12 June 1912,{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}} and finally on 19 June 1912 ''Slieve Bearnagh'' was sold for only £4,350.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=13}}

==With D&J Nicol==
''Slieve Bearnagh''{{'}} buyer was D&J Nicol of [[Dundee]] on the east coast of Scotland, with whom she became the largest pleasure steamer on the [[Firth of Tay]].<ref name=Paddle>{{cite web |url= http://www.paddlesteamers.info/Firth%20of%20Tay.htm |last=Ferguson |first=Gillon |title=Firth of Tay; Tay Excursion Steamers |work=paddlesteamers.info |publisher=Tramscape |accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref> From Dundee she made various excursions: along the coast of [[Angus]] to [[Arbroath]] and [[Montrose, Angus|Montrose]], around the [[Inchcape]] lighthouse, and across to [[St Andrews]] in [[Fife]].<ref name=Paddle/>

==With the Royal Navy==
Sources disagree as to when ''Slieve Bearnagh'' entered [[Royal Navy]] service. The [[Admiralty]] may have requisitioned her in 1915, used her as an auxiliary [[Minesweeper (ship)|minesweeper]] and then bought her in October 1917.<ref name=Clyde/> According to another source the Admiralty did not requisition her until 1917.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=13}} However, sources agree that in January 1919 she served as hospital carrier ship ''HC5''.{{sfn|Patterson|1982|pp=13–14}}<ref name=Clyde/>

''Slieve Bearnagh'' was scrapped at [[Inverkeithing]]{{sfn|Patterson|1982|p=14}} in Fife on 7 June 1923.<ref name=Clyde/>

